<br>
Sorry melee dmg isn't so simple unfortunately. If most hits were really for max and few missed as is in fact the case with say lvl 20 orc centurions in EC then a rogue would do obscene dmg.  In reality casters aren't that much better nor worse off as far as mitigation and avoidance than velks spiders (45-48 about) While your AC may be lower your also a lot higher lvl.  In reality unbuffed bsing all the time I probably wouldn't do more than 70dps average vs the spiders. Keep in mind the normal figures you see for rogues are buffed as we do NOT solo worth shit.   Hitting most hits for max would put me between 200 and 300 dps a figure I'm quite sure I never achieve.  I will gladly verify this fact with you next time we raid together.<br>
<br>
I've found personally that there is also btw a definate difference between naked caster ac and geared caster ac too. Naked casters go down FAST.<br>
<br>
Also before I would care one bit about any issue mages may have there are a few ummm strategies you can use vs pure melee.<br>
<br>
Pet kiting. Run around in a circle while your pet does the dmg for ya. Casting optional.  Since the pure melee can't channel through pet dmg if the pet has expedience the melee can't debuff the pet.  If the caster just runs away the pet WILL kill the melee or force him to run.<br>
<br>
DS.  Use a DS potion AND your own ds then prevent normal dispelling with the simple trick of clicking to insta items.  Your own ds is actually suffiecent here if you don't want to waste the money.  Without wands the melee has as good as lost espcially if as a rogue they must duel wield.<br>
<br>
Levitate and block dispelling as above. Without wands you can't lose.  If your wanded run away and come back releved.<br>
<br>
<br>
LoS exploiting.  Made especially easy via /pet attack /assist<br>
<br>
Ghosting.  Do the circle jerk up and down hills till you ghost then cast at will.<br>
<br>
I would counter your ascertion that mages are unbalanced vs pure melee because you have no lures as wizards do with the fact that I and the other pure melee classes can't simply root your pet as hybrids do and its basicly an unresistable dot for the duration of the fight.  Made especially nasty if you choose not to fight much and let your pet carry the fight.  Whether you enjoy using all or none of the strategies above if they aren't adressed they ARE available to you and if not to you to more unscrupulous members of your class.  Balance must be based on what people can do not what nice people like yourself do.<br>
<br>
If you counter that pet kiting makes melees run I would say you should stop to cast enough that they think they have a chance but not enough to lose the fight.  Have fun.<br>
<br>
I would maintain basicly that vs a pure melee mages are perfectly viable in a real pvp environment and that rogue dmg is not in need of being situationally lowered. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/umearisthecowslayer.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mearis The Cowslayer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/29/02 6:12:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=98>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: In reply to Mearis</span><hr size=1> Aerimus, I am talking about in dungeon pvp, not outdoor pvp where melees take a huge disadvantage... also remember mages do not get absecond/shadowstep, so if you choose to use pumace I have no choice but to run, I cannot shadowstep and refresh skin like a wizard can, and if wish to root the pet just get some wooly silken nets, or dispell the sow from it and just ignore it...<br>
